l war efforts, their participation challenged the imagined homogeneity of Canada as a British nation. From soldiers overseas to workers on the home front – and from the cultural ties of imperial pageantry to the bonds of race and class – Fighting with the Empire examines the paradox of a national contribution to an imperial war effort. This insightful collection of connected case studies explores the middle ground between narratives that celebrate the emergence of a nation through warfare and those that equate Canadian nationalism with British imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th centuryvCase studies. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh1 aBjorge, Mikhail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrazier, Eirik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalstead, Claire L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeelan, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarti, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarti, Steve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPratt, William John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, William John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShaw, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheffield, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalbot, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z97831